<TEXT>
woodsy owl and his give a hoot dont 
pollute refrain are the latest victims in the battle between 
loggers and environmentalists to save the spotted owl 
smokey bear will continue to visit schools near the siuslaw 
national forest as an antifire crusader but his pal woodsy wont 
be coming along 
right now is not the time to have woodsy in the limelight 
said norm hesseldahl public affairs officer for the forest the 
emotions are running pretty high on the spotted owl issue right 
now 
hesseldahl said wednesday the decision to keep woodsy out of the 
schools was made in conjunction with the state department of 
forestry which cosponsors the visits 
woodsy is only being banned in schools in western oregons 
siuslaw forest area hesseldahl said his poster still will be used 
at campgrounds and other places urging people not to pollute 
we certainly dont want to get woodsy and the spotted owl 
confused in the kids minds hesseldahl said 
the northern spotted owl has been the focus of the battle over 
logging in the old growth forests a recent scientific report 
recommends that huge tracts of old growth lands including at the 
siuslaw national forest be preserved to prevent the owl from 
extinction the old growth forests are the main source of timber on 
federal land in western oregon 
</TEXT>
