<DOCNO> AP900413-0003 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
in the venerated church of the holy sepulcher 
the center of easter week activities exactly 43 lamps burn over 
the tomb where tradition holds the crucified christ was buried 
thirteen each are tended by greek orthodox roman catholic and 
armenian clerics and four belong to the egyptian copts 
the jealously guarded division of duties reflects a complicated 
system of caretaking that applies to church altars candlesticks 
icon sites and other church property 
the system was set up in the 1850s by ruling ottoman turks to 
resolve centuries of unseemly squabbles among christian sects for 
control of the shrine 
the tolerance of the four main christian sects caring for the 
church is tested anew each easter season when thousands of pilgrims 
from all denominations flood the church to commemorate the passion 
death and resurrection of christ 
daniel rossing an israeli expert on christianity who formerly 
served as a government mediator in church disputes says that 
problems during the holy days generally are unintentional 
processions get going the wrong way or zealous tourists block 
aisles he said 
fistfights broke out in the past when exhuberant youth groups 
danced out of their assigned spaces and onto the turf reserved for 
others he added 
pity the police who have to sort it all out rossing said 
not only in arabic and english but in russian greek 
armenian 
the church will be more congested than usual this year because 
the eastern rite and latin churches are celebrating easter 
simultaneously for the first time since 1987 and for the last time 
this century 
their feasts generally are a week to five weeks apart because of 
differences in the julian calendar of the eastern churches and the 
gregorian calendar used in the west 
the potential for problems is greatest on good friday when the 
procession route of pilgrims retracing christs walk to calvary 
crosses the paths of moslems headed to friday prayers and jews 
going to sabbath evening prayers at the western wall the last 
remnant of the ancient jewish temple 
moslems and jews may be out in greater numbers than usual too 
because easter week also overlaps ramadan the moslem holy month of 
fasting and passover the eightday jewish holiday commemorating 
the israelites flight from egypt 
israels tourism ministry says 45000 visitors are expected in 
jerusalem for the holidays the highest number since the start of 
the palestinian uprising against israeli rule more than two years 
ago 
we will have plenty of police at sensitive spots police 
spokesman uzi sandori said 
the fire department is prepared too for the dazzling and 
potentially inflamatory miracle of the holy fire by orthodox 
christians on saturday 
as the flame from torches in the sepulcher is passed to 
thousands of candlecarrying worshipers inside the church more 
than two dozen jerusalem firefighters will wield special 
extinguishers to douse the inevitable hair and clothing fires 
the church of the holy sepulcher a dark and dusky doubledomed 
basilica that covers the sites where tradition holds christ was 
crucified and buried is sacred to many christians 
the first church on the site was built in the 4th century by the 
byzantine emperor constantine whose mother queen helena traveled 
to jerusalem in 327 ad to identify the scenes of christs passion 
orthodox domination of the church gave way to roman primacy 
after the byzantine basilica was destroyed by a fanatical egyptian 
caliph and it was rebuilt in the 12th century by the european 
crusaders 
in succeeding years under arab and then ottoman turkish rulers 
the orthodox and latin rites resorted to bribes secret agreements 
and international diplomacy in their battle for supremacy 
the jealousy is such that it took the rival church leaders until 
1959 to agree on a stillincomplete restoration program to repair 
damage from a massive 1808 fire and devastating 1927 earthquake 
the greek orthodox are working alone to fix the dome over 
christs tomb so their control of the area wont be challenged 
the rev jerome murphyoconnor a dominican priest and new 
testament scholar says the ottoman status quo agreement may have 
resolved most property disputes but has not resolved spiritual ones 
one hopes for peace but the ear is assailed by a cacophony of 
warring chants he wrote in his guidebook the holyland one 
desires holiness only to encounter a jealous possessiveness 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

