<TEXT>
another fugitive student leader of the crushed 
prodemocracy movement has escaped china through an underground 
railroad which is still operating 10 months after the crackdown on 
dissent a reliable source said 
i want everybody to know that the channel is still alive 
theres still hope said the source who is close to the 
railroad the source refused to be identified further and asked 
that the date of the interview not be published for security 
reasons 
he refused to divulge details of the escape route 
the source said wang chaohua fled china on or about jan 7 she 
was on a list of 21 students sought by the chinese government for 
leading demonstrations last spring for more freedom in the 
communist country wang 38 was by far the oldest person on the 
list and exerted a strong influence over the others 
the source said he did not know where she has settled in the 
west 
the chineselanguage hong kong economic journal reported 
thursday that wang had escaped to an unnamed destination and would 
meet with other exiled dissidents at an appropriate time 
the underground railroad brought out several prominent student 
and intellectual dissidents soon after june 4 when the chinese 
army killed hundreds if not thousands of people in central 
beijing as it crushed the prodemocracy movement 
in late december china announced the arrests of five residents 
of this british colony and of macao a nearby portuguese enclave 
on charges of trying to smuggle dissidents out of the country the 
prodemocracy movement had widespread support in the territories 
which both revert to chinese rule later this decade 
chinas official xinhua news agency quoted police as saying the 
arrests dealt a major blow to the overseas reactionary forces who 
attempted to use hong kong and macao as sanctuaries for criminals 
it said china would punish severely those who dare to plot and 
ship wanted criminals out of the mainland 
but prodemocracy chinese fugitives are continuing to reach the 
west 
student leader chai ling and her husband feng congde recently 
emerged in france after fleeing china about two weeks ago both 
were on the mostwanted list 
the source refused to comment when asked if the railroad played 
a role in their escape but he said the channel was responsible for 
the escape of wang and a few less prominent people this year he 
refused to name the others 
the lengthy period the three student leaders were able to spend 
as fugitives inside china would indicate there is still popular 
support for the prodemocracy movement 
wang was a postgraduate student at the chinese academy of social 
sciences she played a role akin to that of senior adviser to other 
movement leaders who were much younger and generally less mature 
wang did not have the charisma that thrust other student 
leaders such as wuer kaixi into the international limelight but 
in private she would speak passionately about democracy in china 
the hong kong economic journal said wang wanted to seek 
democratic change through dialogue with the government it said she 
was opposed to the tiananmen square hunger strike that other 
students called to press their demands 
on the first night of the hunger strike last may wang sobbed in 
the middle of the square as arguments raged around her over what 
tactics students should take to keep the movement alive 
five of the 21 students on the wanted list are now known to have 
escaped china to the west wang chai feng wuer and li lu 
about 10 others are either known to be in jail including wang 
dan whose name topped the wanted list or are believed to have 
been apprehended by authorities 
when asked if he thought the underground railroad would be able 
to bring any remaining fugitive student leaders out of the country 
the source said im not optimistic and im not pessimistic ill 
say the chances are 5050 
</TEXT>
