<TEXT>
the indian peasant who tradition holds first 
saw the virgin of guadalupe will be beautified during pope john 
paul iis visit to mexico the archbishop of mexico city said 
the ceremony will be held during a mass at the basilica of 
guadalupe shortly after the pope arrives in mexico on may 6 
cardinal ernesto corripio ahumada said thursday at a news 
conference 
the ceremony is a step toward the canonization of juan diego a 
weaver of reed mats who was born in 1474 and died in 1548 
according to evidence presented to support juan diegos 
canonization the virgin appeared to him four times in mexico city 
in 1531 and cured his dying uncle 
tradition holds that when diego opened his cloak to present 
roses blooming out of season to the skeptical bishop as a sign of 
the truth of his story the flowers tumbled out and the virgins 
image appeared imprinted in their place 
the cloak is on display at the basilica built on the hill where 
the virgin first appeared to diego 
our lady of guadalupe is revered by mexicans and other latin 
americans who make pilgrimages to the shrine and bring tokens of 
thanks for miracles they attribute to her 
the popes weeklong visit to mexico is scheduled to end on may 
13 
