<TEXT>
wool and mohair producers are collecting 100 
million in support payments under a controversial program critics 
say should be revised or scrapped 
others contend the national wool act of 1954 has stemmed the 
downward plunge in us wool production and has helped keep 
thousands of small producers in business by providing payments when 
market prices are low 
the agriculture department announced thursday that the 100 
million in payments for 1989 which are to begin immediately will 
be split equally between wool and mohair producers 
last years federal support level for shorn wool was 177 per 
pound but the national average market price was only 124 per 
pound mohair supports were set at nearly 459 per pound while 
the 1989 average market price was 158 per pound 
the usda announcement on wool and mohair subsidies followed a 
report this week by the general accounting office urging that the 
congress should consider the need for the wool and mohair program 
as lawmakers draft the 1990 farm bill 
since price supports for wool and mohair were established in 
1954 federal subsidies to producers have totaled about 2 billion 
the gao said 
when congress wrote the law wool was considered a strategic 
material required for national security it has not been classified 
as such since 1960 said the gao the investigative arm of congress 
one of the objectives was to encourage the production of wool in 
such a way as to assure a viable domestic industry the report 
said 
although mohair which is clipped from angora goats was not 
included in the wool programs broad objectives the law also 
includes mohair in its payment provisions 
the gao reported in 1982 that despite subsidies us wool 
production has continued to decline and the new report which was 
prepared at the request of rep charles e schumer dny said 
those findings are still valid 
from 1981 through 1988 about 665 million in wool payments 
were made the report said during this period domestic wool 
production continued its morethan30year decline from 110 
million pounds in 1981 to 89 million pounds in 1988 
but the gao acknowledged that studies by the industry and others 
show that wool payments have provided income assurance to 
producers have had a stabilizing effect on the industry and have 
helped slow the decline in us wool production 
even so gao estimated that in 1988 the additional output of 
wool attributable to the program cost taxpayers 304 per pound 
while the average market price of wool produced that year was only 
138 per pound 
the report said that usda wool payments in 1986 the most 
recent year available to investigators totaled 104 million and 
were made to 125378 producers 
of the total 51868 payments were less than 100 each 
representing more than 41 percent of the total more than 102000 
were less than 500 each representing almost 82 percent of the 
1986 total 
but in dollars those 500orless payments made up only 134 
percent of the 104 million total the biggest category for payment 
size was in the 1000to25000 range in which 12209 producers 
collected 485 million or about 47 percent of the years total 
payments of more than 25000 went to 673 producers who got 
344 million or 33 percent of the total 
although there was no comparable breakdown for mohair the gao 
report showed that mohair payments in 1986 totaled 427 million 
and have increased significantly since then 
in 1988 mohair producers collected 471 million compared with 
414 million for wool that was the first time since the program 
began that mohair payments exceeded wool subsidies 
the report said there are only about 12000 mohair producers 
roughly onetenth the number of wool producers and that their 
payments in 1988 averaged about 3925 each compared with 360 for 
wool 
most of the wool payments of less than 100 are concentrated in 
the midwest and the southwest the report said thus elimination 
of the program would affect producers in those areas more than 
others 
according to the director of the navajo wool and mohair 
marketing industry in shiprock nm an estimated 10000 to 15000 
sheep producers are located on the navajo reservation 
while not all of those producers receive wool program 
payments about 7000 to 10000 do and each maintains an average 
of about 20 sheep the report said the director said that 
about 90 percent of the participating producers receive wool 
payments of less than 100 each year 
most of these producers are in the four corners area of arizona 
new mexico utah and colorado and elimination of the small 
payments would likely have a detrimental effect on them the 
report said 
furthermore it added because most of the lamb meat 
produced is used by the navajos as a food source wool sales 
combine with the wool payments general provide the principal income 
derived from their sheep 
the gao also was told by a spokesman for the wool forum inc of 
henning minn that the small payments are a worthwhile 
investment in the wool industry of the future because many new 
producers are from nonfarm backgrounds and are reluctant to risk 
large investment because of their lack of experience 
in his opinion the wool program adds that little extra 
financial encouragement that makes these new producers go ahead 
with their investments the gao said 
