the veterans affairs department is moving to 
head off a loss of registered nurses with legislation that would 
bring their pay in line with what nurses elsewhere receive 
by introducing its bill this week the va also is moving the 
bush administration closer to embracing competitive pay for all 
government employees 
federal agencies have been looking at competitive or locality 
pay as a means of recruiting and keeping workers 
competitive pay bases salaries on current rates paid in a 
community for comparable positions the federal office of personnel 
management has proposed a system that includes adjustments for 
local pay but also for certain employees links pay raises to job 
performance 
the house and senate veterans affairs committees have separate 
proposals for raising nursing pay as well 
under the new bill a va hospital nursing home or other 
facility would be able to use pay data from nonva facilities in an 
area to establish community rates the community rates would be 
paid only if those local rates exceed the national pay scale for va 
nurses 
the va employs 35000 registered nurses at its hospitals 
clinics and nursing homes making it the largest such employer in 
the country 
the nationally set base pay for a va registered nurse is 
18174 the american nurses association says the national average 
starting pay for a registered nurse is 25261 
the va already has been able to adjust pay to meet local rates 
but the process is so slow that the agencys salary levels still 
fall behind those of private employers 
the department was paying special rates at 130 of its 172 
medical centers a year ago veterans affairs secretary edward j 
derwinski said in a letter accompanying his legislative proposal 
even with the special rates va has not been able to offer 
competitive salaries at certain geographic locations such as 
boston southern california and new york city derwinski said 
