the defense department estimates that the 
price tag for bringing 95 major weapons programs from design to 
full production is 8438 billion 31 billion more than 
projections made three months earlier 
in issuing its report thursday the pentagon blamed the 
significant jump in the last quarter of 1989 on revised inflation 
rates and a slight increase in the number of missiles aircraft and 
other weapons president bush sought 
among the major increases were the estimated costs for the 
landbased midgetman nuclear missile the c17 cargo plane and the 
ddg51 destroyer the pentagon is reconsidering the latter two 
programs 
the socalled selected acquisition report provides a 
snapshot as of last dec 31 of expected overall costs for 95 
major weapons systems if bushs defense budget is enacted as 
proposed 
however the overall estimate may change because congress or 
defense secretary dick cheney may limit production on or terminate 
some weapons systems including several under review 
the previous report released in september predicted the 
overall cost of the major systems would be 8066 billion 
the difference in the two figures is 372 billion which 
includes the 31 billion increase and an estimate of 62 billion 
for the navys fixed distributed system a classified ocean 
surveillance project 
among the estimated increases was the cost of the midgetman 
missile which rose 19 billion or 35 percent to 73 billion 
the pentagon said the jump was primarily the result of restoring 
costs expected all along but excluded last year because of the way 
bush and congress handled the missile program in the current 
defense budget 
the fiscal 1990 budget contains less than 250 million for the 
mobile singlewarhead missile with those funds the midgetman 
program amounted to a research and development project the 
pentagon said 
