<DOCNO> AP900413-0041 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
harvard university president derek bok 
struck back at conservative critics of higher education saying 
problems stem from a decade of tax cuts and federal deficits rather 
than liberal education practices 
in his 19th annual report issued thursday bok warned that the 
criticism could end up hurting higher education 
conservatives who rose to prominence in the political climate of 
the 1980s saw universities as liberal strongholds populated by 
cocksure opinionated professors bok wrote in the 40page report 
these conservative critics have attacked higher education more 
savagely during the past 10 years than at any time in my memory 
bok said 
most of the charges are flawed because they ignore basic 
conflicts and contradictions in the demands society makes on 
universities he wrote 
continued criticism of this kind threatens to do needless 
damage to the public confidence so important to maintaining a 
strong system of colleges and universities 
what is needed is not an end to criticism but a criticism 
that is less given to rhetorical excess more careful with its 
criteria for judgment bok wrote 
bok addressed several areas of controversy including the 
conflict between teaching and research last month the faculty of 
harvard medical school approved a set of guidelines governing 
outside work for faculty members 
one signal comes from all the critics who deplore the neglect 
of teaching and the stress that universities place on published 
work bok said the other makes the opposite point through a 
system of powerful incentives and rewards that offers fame fortune 
and ample funding to successful scientists and scholars 
bok said teachers are not always motivated by private gain when 
undertaking outside pursuits and said that research usually 
benefits a university but bok did say schools need to delineate 
how much time can be spent on outside pursuits he said 
restrictions are inadequate at many institutions 
bok also decried what he called hostile publicity about 
rising tuition costs bok said most news reports about expensive 
tuition are focused on a few highpowered universities such as 
harvard stanford yale or princeton when in fact most 
undergraduates attend public universities where tuition is less 
than 2000 per year 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900413-0042 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the mayors of oakland and san francisco 
heaped scorn on the federal emergency management agency over its 
handling of housing relief for people left homeless after the 
october earthquake 
san francisco mayor art agnos accused the agency of behaving as 
if it were protecting the public treasury against the victims of 
the disaster in testifying thursday before the house subcommittee 
on housing and community development 
the 71magnitude quake that struck northern california on oct 
17 killed 67 people and did millions of dollars in property damage 
 
agnos and oakland mayor lionel wilson complained that the agency 
displayed arrogance and a lack of compassion toward people 
stunned and suddenly homeless 
alameda county supervisor don perata said im here to 
communicate a lot of anger a lot of frustration oakland has over 
the way fema has treated us if these people worked for me in 
alameda county they would be summarily dismissed 
there may be difficulties within a bureaucracy but there 
should be no excuse for treating people you are empowered to serve 
with disrespect callousness and as though they were the enemy 
seeking to come into your home in the dark of night to steal your 
silverware perata said 
one fema rule required that applicants had to have lived in a 
