<TEXT>
chinese leaders are warning of domestic religious 
and ethnic conflict apparently fearing the nationalist tumult in 
neighboring central asia could spread to mongols manchus moslems 
and tibetans in china 
a spread of ethnic violence and religious fundamentalism from 
soviet asia and democratic impulses from mongolia could threaten 
beijings longnurtured concept of unity and harmony between han 
chinese and the nations 55 minorities 
martial law has been in effect in the tibetan capital of lhasa 
for more than a year following recurrent antichinese riots 
last week troops were reportedly dispatched to three cities 
near the soviet border to put down unrest among moslem ethnic 
groups the government has barred foreign travelers and journalists 
from the region 
premier li peng in february said a tiny number of separatists 
under the mantle of nationalism and religion oppose socialism and 
sabotage the unity of all chinese nationalities 
china he told officials in charge of minority affaris should 
wipe out all separatist activities while they are still in the 
embryonic stage 
beijings minority problem pales before that of the soviet 
union where almost 50 percent of the population is nonrussian in 
china the 86 million members of nonhan ethnic groups are less 
than 8 percent of the 11 billion population and many have long 
been assimilated into chinese culture 
but ethnic groups inhabit lands comprising 60 percent of chinas 
territory stretching from the himalayas of the southwest to the 
silk road deserts of the west and the endless steppes of the north 
tibet has been the most volatile region many tibetans 
stubbornly resist chinas claims to sovereignty and dozens have 
died in antichinese riots in lhasa since late 1987 
at least 4000 tibetans demonstratd in lhasa last month to mark 
the anniversary of martial law according to spokesmen for tibets 
exiled spiritual leader the dalai lama but china denied the 
report beijing refused entry to all foreign journalists and 
tourists and operators didnt put phone calls through 
the buddhist tibetans deeply resent chinas past policies of 
religious and cultural persecution their feelings are shared by 
the uygurs and other moslem groups more than half the 14 million 
people of arid xinjiang uygur autonomous region to the north 
xinjiang borders on soviet kazakhstan kirghizia and 
tadzhikistan and shares cultural ties with their restless peoples 
in addition to 73 million huis and 6 million uygurs scatterings 
of kazaks kirghiz tatars russians and tajiks are also found in 
xinjiang and other border provinces 
