that forced that countrys communist party leadership to resign 
but according to one soviet diplomat the chinese believe there is 
a real danger the mongol reform movement will spill over into 
chinas inner mongolia 
some 35 million mongols live in the region more than the 2 
million ethnic brothers across the border in mongolia but chinas 
mongols who conquered the country under genghis khan in the 13th 
century are outnumbered in inner mongolia by 18 million hans they 
also lack the cultural and religious unity of the tibetans and 
moslems 
chinas antireligion and forced assimilation policies of the 
1950s and 1960s led to bloody clashes including a failed tibetan 
uprising in 1959 that drove the dalai lama into exile 
since the late 1970s beijing has tried to make amends by 
rebuilding places of worship and encouraging traditional culture 
and language 
minorities are exempted from the onechild population policy and 
are beneficiaries of educational and antipoverty programs the 
government pledges it will improve its record of appointing 
nonhans to official positions 
at least in the south along the border with vietnam laos and 
burma the policy seems to be working 
the 14 million zhuangs chinas largest minority group the 
55 million yi people and the 5 million miaos live quietly in 
remote farming villages known more for festivals and colorful 
costumes than political consciousness 
