<TEXT>
years of financial hardship have touched 
off record numbers of suicides and raised the incidence of 
drugtaking depression and child abuse in rural america officials 
say 
mental health problems are growing faster in rural areas than in 
cities but rural mental health services remain woefully 
inadequate according to a parade of witnesses thursday at the 
first of three nationwide hearings by the national advisory mental 
health council and the national mental health leadership forum 
rural america has gone through some wrenching times said 
bob bergland executive vice president of the national rural 
electric cooperative association 
mining timber and farming went to pot in the past decade 
he said the repercussions were painful record numbers of farm 
foreclosures high unemployment and a death spiral for many rural 
enterprises 
paul lasley associate professor of sociology at iowa state 
university said the isolation fierce independence and fear of 
being stigmatized set rural residents apart from urbanites with 
mental disorders 
when adversity struck in rural america the victims were often 
left alone to deal with their problems he said 
lasley recalled how one central iowa farmer asked to resign from 
his churchs board of deacons once it was learned he had lost his 
farm 
at the very time that social support was needed his own 
church cast him aside he said 
myrt armstrong executive director of the mental health 
association in north dakota said that out of 70 suicides in north 
dakota last year 20 were directly farmrelated 
in the heartland we have always lived by rules like where 
theres a will theres a way or hard work never killed anyone 
or even you reap what you sow she said 
but those who have had a steel determination and have worked 
extremely hard are reaping a bitter harvest often ending in 
depression and suicide 
that stoic independence admired in rural people has become a 
roadblock to seeking help bergland said 
heaven knows youll never get a farmer to walk voluntarily 
into a mental health center and ask someone to hold his hand he 
said 
several who spoke described farm families who cling to their 
privacy and fear letting others in on their problems that in 
turn deepens their isolation raises their anxiety and leads them 
to feeling guilty and ashamed 
the key to restoring the fabric of rural america the experts 
said lies in dispelling the fear of reaching out for help 
bergland suggested that mental health facilities be combined 
with other healthcare centers to lessen the stigma and that 
mental health training be geared more toward the needs of rural 
communities 
said armstrong the only hope for people in this kind of 
trouble lies in other people people who can listen help sort 
things out and make intelligent referrals to other resources 
the fabric of rural life has been torn and once mended will 
never be quite the same again she said healing is possible 
and we hope that if we pay attention to the healing process and 
mend the fabric with care we will wind up with a whole cloth once 
again 
