the county coroner announced his resignation 
amid reports that the high homicide rate is straining his staff 
slowing autopsies and causing bodies to be left on the streets for 
hours 
ronald kornblum 57 will step down july 1 after eight years on 
the job because the administrative job was unfulfilling and he 
wants to resume teaching and writing coroners department 
spokesman bob dambacher said thursday 
the office has come under fire for moving too slowly on 
autopsies leaving bodies at crime and accident scenes for hours 
and most embarrassingly bouncing corpses onto freeways from old 
coroner vehicles with bad door locks 
a recent audit found that staff shortages coupled with a high 
homicide rate is straining the coroners office to the breaking 
point 
kornblum who declined to comment on his resignation took over 
as coroner for the nations most populous county in 1982 
he replaced thomas noguchi who was removed for serving as a 
consultant on cases outside the county 
the lowkey kornblums style contrasted with noguchi the 
coroner to the stars who wrote a bestselling book about his 
betterknown cases 
as the chief medical examinercoroner kornblum directed a staff 
of 160 responsible for an annual caseload of about 18000 deaths 
including 7000 bodies that require autopsies 
overall the report indicates the coroner is fulfilling his 
legal responsibilities but is experiencing operation and managerial 
difficulties los angeles county auditorcontroller mark 
bloodgood said in a letter accompanying the audit 
kornblum said he agreed with most of the reports suggestions 
and that the office was implementing some of them but he said 
certain changes such as processing all bodies in 24 hours were 
impossible 
