<TEXT>
premier li peng will visit the soviet union april 
2326 becoming the first chinese head of government to travel to 
moscow since 1964 the foreign ministry said today 
the ministry said in a statement that li will have an 
extensive and indepth exchange of views with soviet leaders on the 
bilateral relations and major international issues of common 
concern 
li was invited to visit the soviet union in may when soviet 
president mikhail gorbachev made the first trip to beijing by a 
soviet leader in three decades prodemocracy activists in china 
used the visit to promote their demands for reforms but the 
movement was crushed in june 
chinas leaders have since taken a hardline communist approach 
ignoring moscows reform program of glasnost and perestroika 
the exchange of visits has marked the end of decades of 
hostility between the two socialist states and signaled a gradual 
warming of political and economic relations 
soviet sources said li will meet twice with gorbachev in moscow 
and will make a oneday trip to kiev they said it is likely the 
two leaders will sign an agreement to promote bilateral trade and 
an accord of general principles on easing military tensions along 
the 4300mile common border 
china and the soviet union split over ideological differences 
around 1960 and fought a brief border war in 1969 
relations have steadily improved since the mid1980s when 
gorbachev came to power particularly after gorbachev withdrew 
soviet forces from afghanistan and pledged to reduce soviet 
military forces in asia 
however china has emphasized it will never return to the close 
relations with the soviet union it had in the 1950s 
chinese leaders have also distanced themselves from the 
democratic reforms now taking place in the soviet union and east 
europe 
although china has not publicly commented on such actions as the 
soviet communist partys renunciation of its monopoly on power 
internal documents reportedly have branded gorbachev a revisionist 
li studied electrical engineering in the soviet union in the 
1950s and favors traditional sovietstyle central planning and 
emphasis on heavy industry 
