a soviet helicopter pilot who stopped radiation 
spewing from the chernobyl nuclear reactor by dropping tons of sand 
and concrete will undergo a bonemarrow transplant in the united 
states this month doctors say 
anatoly grishchenko 53 made five flights in three days through 
heavy ionizing radiation in a mission to entomb the reactor he 
apparently is the first chernobyl victim to come to the united 
states for medical treatment doctors at fred hutchinson cancer 
research center said thursday 
this is not the normal type of patient we do hope to 
learn some things said dr patrick g beatty an associate 
professor of medicine at the university of washington its new 
territory 
grishchenko has preleukemia typified by low counts of 
platelets needed for clotting and of white blood cells to fight 
infection and disease he said he will stay in seattle for about 
three months after the surgery planned for april 27 beatty said 
soviet authorities said two people died in an explosion and fire 
that destroyed the atomic reactor north of kiev april 26 1986 and 
29 more people later died of injuries 
