victims 
about 4250 bodies of the officers the cream of polands 
intelligentsia called up from the reserves at the start of world 
war ii were found in mass graves near the western russian city of 
smolensk 
the soviets interned the officers at a camp in kozielsk shortly 
after the red army invaded poland at the outbreak of the war at 
the time the soviet union and germany were joined in a 
nonaggression pact 
the remains of more than 10000 other officers held at camps in 
starobielsk and ostashkow have never been found and word on their 
fate remains as a key demand by organizations representing their 
families 
the katyn bodies shot in the back of the head and stacked in 
layers were found by the nazis in april 1943 and immediately used 
for propaganda purposes against the allies 
the soviets maintained that the nazis killed the officers in 
1941 after they invaded the soviet union 
