including sealaunched and airlaunched cruise missiles in the pact 
and on provisions to guard against cheating 
specifically the soviets argued that the treaty should count 
airlaunched cruise missiles carried by tactical fighters as well 
as heavy bombers according to us officials 
the united states wants the rules to cover only heavy bombers 
and to count only those airlaunched cruise missiles with ranges 
above 600 miles the soviets want the range limit to be 360 miles 
the soviets also revived a demand they had dropped last fall 
that the proposed treaty require the two sides to declare limits on 
the number of sealaunched cruise missiles they would deploy 
administration officials have said they are willing to issue a 
separate declaration specifying the maximum number of sealaunched 
cruise missiles they plan to deploy but do not want that statement 
required by the strategic arms treaty 
