<TEXT>
competition for students and drops in 
government support were the main reasons for huge tuition jumps at 
private and public colleges during the 1980s says a new study 
and while experts predict some relief in the 1990s they say the 
price of higher education will still rise faster than inflation 
at least until the baby booms babies start to hit college age 
the report by arthur hauptman an authority on higher education 
finances says the shrinking number of collegeage youths has 
played a major role tuition increases 
the continued decline in this age group through the mid1990s 
suggests that college charges probably will continue to outpace 
inflation for the forseeable future hauptman concludes 
but he adds that it is difficult to imagine that consumers 
will be unlimited in their willingness to pay steadily rising 
college prices and suggests they will rebel at some point against 
price increases that are double the inflation rate 
from 1980 to 1987 the average boost in tuition and fees was 
slightly under 10 percent annually nearly twice inflation 
the college tuition spiral hauptmans report for the 
college board and american council on education concluded that 
cutbacks in state aid during the early 1980s were a major factor in 
tuition increases at public colleges 
private colleges raised tuition to pay for better facilities 
services and faculty salaries in attempts to maintain their share 
of a shrinking pool of potential students the study said the 
schools also used some of the money to expand their own student aid 
programs a need provoked by cuts at the federal level 
furthermore hauptman wrote with stagnating enrollments 
schools could no longer spread fixed costs over a growing number of 
students plus they had to spend more to counsel and recruit 
nontraditional students 
hauptman said an economic downturn in the next few years could 
force public institutions dependent on strained state resources to 
raise tuition but prompt private colleges to hold the line to keep 
from discouraging prospective students 
the trend of the 1980s was in sharp contrast to the late 1970s 
when tuitions and other charges grew more slowly than inflation 
richard rosser president of the national association of 
independent colleges and universities representing 1600 schools 
said colleges had to charge more during the 1980s to catch up with 
needs that had gone unmet during the previous decade 
now there is probably going to be some leveling off and 
perhaps some decrease on the average rosser said but it will 
still be more than the rate of inflation because that doesnt 
relate very well to our true costs 
robert atwell president of the american council on education 
said it would be harder for lowerpriced schools to cut 
expenditures and keep tuition down because they are less 
selective and pretty strained already financially 
but he said a combination of market resistance the politics of 
the issue and a falloff in applications will force a general 
moderation a drop in applications is a powerful statement 
theres been some of that at some of the higherpriced 
institutions atwell said 
charles kolb an assistant education undersecretary for 
planning said his department is taking a a comprehensive look at 
college costs he said preliminary research indicates some colleges 
feel they can control many of the factors that fuel rising tuition 
but declined to be more specific 
a recent study by the associated press found many colleges and 
universities are starting the new decade with some of the smallest 
tuition increases in years 
stanford university raised fixed student fees by 525 percent in 
199091 to 20210 the smallest increase in 15 years and 
considerably less than the 8 percent hike in the current year 
massachusetts institute of technology announced in march its rates 
