<TEXT>
for nine years through deportation and 
wars devastation helena krahelska kept shoes and shirts waiting 
but in 1948 she acknowledged that her beloved husband piotr had 
been among the polish army officers massacred by the soviet secret 
police in katyn forest 
it took the soviet government 42 more years to do the same 
mrs krahelska did not live to hear moscow finally confess 
friday that the crime it blamed on the nazis was actually committed 
by the soviet union in one of the gravest crimes of stalinism 
but her surviving daughter wanda zadrozna received the news 
with eyes filled with tears 
there is a great regret that it took 50 years and the wives of 
those people didnt live until this day mrs zadrozna said 
but whatever happens now it is good that the truth will be 
finally written in history 
mrs zadrozna was 12 when she last saw her father a landowner 
lawyer and town mayor in eastern poland as the soviet army swept 
into poland at the outbreak of world war ii in 1939 it interned 
15000 polish army officers 
we got three letters the last one was from march 5 1940 
mrs zadrozna recalled fingering the plastic wrapping around the 
worn pages that record her fathers last worries about his familys 
fate 
then no one got any letters any more she said 
in 1943 the nazis invading the soviet union unearthed the mass 
graves of officers whose bodies were stacked atop each other most 
were shot in the back of the head 
this news was so horrible no one wanted to believe it we 
treated it as propaganda mrs zadrozna said 
everybody was still waiting my mother had everything for him 
and it wasnt easy because we had nothing sometimes she would 
refresh the clothes because she hoped maybe he would come 
back 
after hiding from red army death squads and barely escaping 
transport to siberia mrs krahelska and her daughters were 
deported west at wars end from the sovietannexed eastern poland 
to the boundaries of the new polish communist state 
mrs krahelska gave up hope for her husband but she was never 
able to bury him or even mourn him openly the communist polish 
government backed the soviet explanation and during the stalinist 
years people died for speaking of such things 
mrs zadrozna remembers her mothers naive effort to get a 
widows pension in 1949 when it turned out my father was at 
katyn she was told to get out of the office as soon as possible 
or else you will find yourself where you dont want to be 
all through those years there were only silent memories only 
symbolic graves with no inscription but everyone knew here they 
should light candles mrs zadrozna said 
for her family the toll also includes another katyn victim her 
fathers brother stanislaw a cousin killed fighting for the allies 
in italy and an aunt a writer who died in a concentration camp 
this is my personal story it is not an exception there are 
different stories none less tragic she said 
but katyn is among the deepest wounds in muchscarred polish 
history 
those killed were doctors scientists professors the elite 
called up from the army reserve as stalin planned their places 
leading poland were taken by sovietbacked functionaries as the 
communists consolidated power after the war 
these were the best of their homeland mrs zadrozna said 
it is not only i who have been missing them personally but the 
whole country has been missing them 
mrs krahelska died at 84 in 1982 when nothing indicated that 
people would talk about this her daughter said and even now 
mrs zadrozna is surprised i never thought that they would 
recognize responsibility 
i have always felt sorry that not everybody has known the 
truth because at home and at school nobody spoke about this 
mrs zadrozna said now everybody who goes to school will know 
the history of this massacre my grandchildren will know the 
truth 
</TEXT>
