a british company accused of preparing steel tubes 
to make a 131footlong gun for iraq called the allegations absurd 
friday and said it had already shipped part of the order to baghdad 
customs officers on thursday seized eight sections of forged 
steel tubing on the docks at middlesbrough after a ministry of 
defense expert said they could be used to build a weapon 
some arms experts said such a gun could hit middle east targets 
hundreds of miles away others doubt the tubes could be used to 
make such a monster gun 
there is no question it could be used as a barrel of a large 
artillery gun to fire a projectile of some considerable size it is 
definitely subject to export licensing controls said douglas 
tweddle chief investigator for the customs and excise office 
iraqi officials and the manufacturer sheffield forgemasters 
say the tubing was intended for use in a petrochemical plant the 
company says the pipe sections were part of an assembly 5118 feet 
long 
i am sure that most people will recognize the absurdity of 
suggestions being made that these pipes are in fact guns company 
spokesman tony peck said 
the company said it had two contracts for 26 sections each and 
had delivered 44 sections to the ministry of industry and minerals 
in baghdad 
some weapons experts had said a gun with a barrel the size of 
the tube seized by customs 131 feet long with a 39inch bore 
could fire nuclear or chemical warheads as far as tehran or tel 
aviv each within 350 miles of iraqs borders 
