<TEXT>
the way many analysts see it the sluggish 
behavior of the stock market in the first few months of 1990 
reflects more than just uncertainty about the outlook for interest 
rates or corporate profits 
stock prices have been left to drift in light trading activity 
they theorize as the very idea of acquisitive risktaking has 
undergone a temporary fall from favor 
the nation is preoccupied right now with cleaning up a series of 
financial messes among them the savings and loan debacle wall 
streets junkbond binge of the 1980s and a welter of bad loans in 
the banking business 
at the same time the freespending consumers of the past decade 
show signs of adopting a new ethic building up their depleted 
savings reserves instead of taking on bold new commitments 
all this tends to put a damper on both the economy and the 
markets which depend on the aggressive pursuit of wealth for much 
of their energy 
some say it raises the threat of a consumerinduced recession 
others worry about the possibility of a credit crunch in which 
constraints on lending create a scarcity of money for investment in 
business housing and bigticket consumer purchases 
but worrisome as these budding trends may be for the immediate 
future observers also argue they could be a significant plus for 
the economy and wall street over the long term 
if all goes right they say what is going on now could clear 
away past excesses and help build a stable base from which future 
opportunities and growth could arise 
the latest example of investors concerns is a sweeping inquiry 
by government regulators into the lending practices of banks which 
has evoked visions of a long dry spell for borrowers 
there is a lot to keep investors jumpy if not downright 
scared says michael sherman investment strategist at shearson 
lehman hutton inc 
are bank regulators going to create such havoc in the 
financial markets as to create a credit crunch and an economic 
downturn is the sampl contraction an openended sewer 
such questions arent easy to answer right now sherman says 
but he argues that the picture nevertheless has its positive side 
if you think the situation is fraught with peril today you 
should be glad the government didnt wait for tomorrow to staunch 
open wounds in the financial fabric at least were not living in a 
fools paradise 
if we survive the cure we will have a chance of living both 
better and longer in a financial sense 
furthermore sherman contends any squeeze on economic activity 
could well have a favorable impact by bringing interest rates down 
that decline would come quickly he adds because the 
areas of the economy most affected are also those that are most 
creditsensitive namely construction and real estate 
most observers agree that in intent at least the drive to 
clean up the financial environment is sensible and directed at the 
right targets 
the question they say is how decisionmakers and the markets 
are able to negotiate the distance between where things stand today 
and the goal 
as neal soss economist at first boston corp defined the 
problem being prudent like being sober or having a high saving 
rate is a good thing but getting prudent like getting sober or 
raising the saving rate involves a certain transitional 
discomfort 
