<TEXT>
when reporter maria montoya first visited key west 
it was just after midnight may 1 1980 and the boatlift of 
refugees from mariel cuba was in full swing 
but ms montoya was on the other side of the cameras 
a us coast guard ship had rescued her her husband eduardo 
and 10 other people packed inside a disabled 18foot boat adrift in 
the gulf stream after completing most of the 90mile journey from 
cuba 
the boatlift was only 10 days old and ms montoya and her 
husband got a warm reception they were cheered as they stepped 
onto us territory and welcomed by us soldiers and volunteer 
workers who gave them food and clothing 
one sight seemed strange though 
i saw 300 men their heads almost shaved sitting on the 
dock she said i asked why are those men sitting apart 
someone told me those are the criminals and the mental patients 
castro is sending us 
the boatlift then was being hailed as the freedom flotilla 
an embarrassment to fidel castros regime and a chance as 
president jimmy carter said to welcome with open arms those 
fleeing oppression 
but before it ended five months later when castro closed the 
port of mariel it had become a disaster costing hundreds of 
millions of dollars stirring murderous crime waves and escalating 
prejudices 
the whole mariel boatlift struck very deep nasty chords in 
the american public said frank sharry executive director of the 
immigration policy group the national forum 
marielito became a derisive label meaning misfits crazies 
hardcore criminals 
but you know what most of them did just fine sharry said 
ms montoya now 33 who risked a relatively comfortable life as 
a cuban radio and television actress is among dozens successful in 
the media and the arts others have made their marks in fields such 
as business education and sports and several boatlift children 
became honor students and valedictorians but the stigma remains 
even after the initial crime waves blamed on mariel refugees 
subsided their image was furthered by such cases as the 1984 
slaying of a miami beach police officer 1987 riots and 
hostagetaking by refugees in atlanta and oakdale la federal 
prisons and the fire last month that claimed 87 lives at the happy 
land social club in the bronx in which a mariel refugee is 
