officials of the embassy situation 
within weeks the distantseeming foreign policy question became 
his states crisis when castro abruptly announced that mariel was 
open 
a ragtag armada of boats chartered by cubanamericans anxious 
to pick up relatives set sail and returned with some surprising 
cargo along with parents aunts and uncles friends and former 
political prisoners the boats brought passengers picked by the 
cuban government 
castro and the statecontrolled media crowed that the united 
states was getting the bums and scum 
we dont want them castro told a cheering havana crowd 
we dont need them 
by throwing in cuban miscreants castro portrayed the boatlift 
as a sweeping out of his society 
unleashed on american society from spartan cuban gulags the 
boatlifts criminal element spurred street crime explosions in 
miamis little havana and among the elderly of miami beach then 
spread into other us cities 
their crimes were the worst of many problems 
it had a human impact by adding 125000 people to the 
population reflected graham it contributed to a tense 
community situation by surfacing tensions i think it contributed 
to the may 1980 liberty city race riots 
castro was able to unload criminals and undesirable elements 
and there was an immediate and continuing strain on health and 
social institutions he said 
with the cuban economy stagnant and the government increasingly 
isolated by the crumbling of the socialist bloc us officials say 
they have readied contingency plans to prevent a new mariel 
castro has used opening up his borders as a tactic to relieve 
pressure graham said were in a dilemma because our national 
tradition is that we provide sanctuary but we ought to discourage 
a new boatlift and make sure its an orderly movement 
about onefifth of the mariel refugees had served jail time in 
cuba but for the great majority it was for petty offenses or 
political crimes 
today most authorities say fewer than 10 percent of the 
refugees were criminals some 2600 still are in federal custody 
173 were returned to cuba under a suspended immigration agreement 
and an estimated 4000 are in various state and local prisons 
i can tell you now that the impact was positive said miami 
city manager cesar odio only a small percentage created 
problems most have been good citizens but the immediate impact 
was negative for all cubans 
a gallup poll at the time indicated that cubans usually 
considered an immigration success story had become one of the 
nations most unpopular alien groups 
that image made resettling the immigrants difficult many were 
placed in refugee camps at us military bases in the florida 
panhandle arkansas pennsylvania and wisconsin frustrated 
refugees rioted in arkansas and there were disturbances in the 
other camps 
carter declared the boatlift illegal a month after it began 
boat captains were fined and had their vessels confiscated 
but it was too late about 70000 cubans already had arrived 
and more were on their way 
the only other time castro had opened a port camarioca in 1965 
the total number of refugees was fewer than 6000 
in the beginning we completely missed the boat said 
gunther o wagner who worked for the state departments 
cubanhaitian task force how did we know would we get 300 
3000 10000 we got 125000 
the criminal image and the large number of single men thousands 
of them homosexuals made finding sponsors difficult 
a lot of groups just gave up said sharry the church 
groups we were used to working with were nice suburban churches 
and now heres fileno with a tattoo on his eyelid ready to go to 
the church picnic 
</TEXT>
