<TEXT>
since five handcuffed cubans from the 1980 mariel 
boatlift boarded a government jet in december 1988 for the homeland 
they fled 168 more have followed 
some numbed by their years in jail went voluntarily feeling 
that as bad as cuba may be it beat the prospect of an indefinite 
stretch in a maximumsecurity prison in the united states 
but thousands more who have completed their sentences remain 
behind bars with no idea when or even if they will get out many 
eventually are freed but those identified as the tougher cases are 
not 
by law the united states can hold them as long as it wants 
even for life although no charges remain against them 
of those who have gone back to cuba we know of a few who have 
been released a few who are still in jail said decatur ga 
attorney gary leshaw who represents many detainees 
of those who went back id say about 30 of them went 
voluntarily not because they wanted to go back to cuba but because 
they thought they had a better chance for release there he said 
about once a month a few more judged deportable are taken from 
the federal prison at talladega ala to birmingham for the 
90minute flight back to cuba 
the great majority of the 125000 marielitos as they are 
known are lawabiding and have adjusted to american life in the 
decade since their arrival 
an estimated 80000 have become american citizens and the 
others are on immigration parole and have been told they wont be 
bothered if they stay out of trouble 
thus while marielitos have been in this country for a decade 
technically they arent really here and never have been the 
courts have ruled they have no constitutional guarantees 
people who enter the united states illegally must be released 
after six months if their native countries will not take them back 
but mariel cubans named for the port from which they left in an 
exodus authorized by cuban president fidel castro dont fit that 
category 
they are classed as excludable aliens 
i felt and i still feel that any person the attorney general 
holds beyond a reasonable time is entitled to a hearing to see if 
that reason is a sufficient reason said us district judge 
marvin shoob of atlanta who ruled in 1983 that the mariel cubans 
were entitled to limited due process 
he was reversed by a federal appeals court and the us supreme 
court declined to hear the case shoob said it is unlikely the case 
will get into the appeals court system again and that congressional 
legislative action is the only apparent avenue for change 
it was not a happy episode in us jurisprudence shoob said 
but he said the vast majority of those who deserve to get 
out have gotten out 
initially cuba agreed to take back the 2726 cubans jailed as 
of dec 14 1984 it accepted 201 before castro ended the agreement 
in 1985 in retaliation for the american broadcast of radio marti 
beamed at cuba 
of the 201 156 were reported free in cuba at one point after 
spending time in medical quarantine 
in late 1987 cuba agreed to accept the rest at a rate of up to 
100 a month sparking riots at federal prisons in atlanta and 
oakdale la where about 3800 cubans who had finished their 
sentences were detained by the us immigration and naturalization 
service 
of the 3800 leshaw said about twothirds have been freed 
after reviews by special justice department panels the reviews 
were one of the concessions made to the cubans in custody during 
the riots for surrendering control of the prisons 
but shoob said the review concession was less than it seemed 
under the agreements there are no requirements for the 
government to supply attorneys or for the cases to be heard before 
disinterested parties shoob said 
duke austin an ins spokesman in washington dc said reviews 
are all the law provides for 
it is not a judicial process it is an administrative record 
review only he said the majority are being paroled out 
the ins has paroled every detained cuban at one time or another 
but about 60 they all had a chance 
the 60 were identified on arrival as hardened criminals or 
severe mental cases and have been held since 1980 the rest are 
jailed for things that occurred after they got here about 2600 
are in ins custody now and the agency has detainers on another 
4000 who are serving sentences austin said 
lawyers who represent the cubans complain of arrogance and 
ignorance on the part of some review panel members 
i have never seen such a farce in my life reads a memo from 
lafayette la attorney judith gardner who represented a woman 
jailed for theft 
i will never forget the panel members they were cynical and 
accusatory ms gardner said they were disrespectful and 
seemed to revel in playing god over the lives of these people 
she said they accused her client of crimes she had never been 
charged with and told her she never would be released to an area 
near where her mother lives 
the treatment of those returned to cuba remains uncertain 
roberto martinez sent back to cuba in march 1989 wrote to an 
american friend from jail there we received a good attention 
from them but it only was the first days but we would not make any 
communications with our family during 54 days and we just didnt 
know why 
martinez letter said he was moved to another prison and allowed 
to see a judge 
he said that we are peligrosos dangerous ones and also he 
said that we are not ready to make our lives within the community 
in other words we have received two and the half year sentence with 
the charge of peligrosidad dangerousness he wrote 
the letter said he hoped to be free by the end of 1989 
whether he was is undetermined 
