<TEXT>
in the early 1970s robert mapplethorpe took his 
first photographs with a polaroid camera it was the perfect tool 
for radical art 
what was radical about his work was not so much the subject 
matter but the process and materials he applied to a stagnant form 
adding fabric texture tone 
form and technique however are not what spring to mind these 
days when considering the late artist today it is the rough 
images he immortalized oral sex bondage homosexual fondling 
that make him an important force in 20thcentury art 
perhaps mapplethorpe never fully realized his destiny as an 
artist he died in march 1989 at the age of 42 of complications 
from acquired immune deficiency syndrome 
in death he is embroiled in controversy and has become a symbol 
for artistic freedom 
a mapplethorpe exhibit last june at the corcoran gallery of art 
in washington was canceled after sen jesse helms rnc declared 
some of the artists photographs to be obscene helms objections 
resulted in a move by congress to limit federal funds to the arts 
mapplethorpes works have been shown at the whitney museum of 
art in new york and in chicago philadelphia boston berkeley 
calif and hartford conn but a grand jury this month indicted 
the contemporary arts center in cincinnati ohio on obscenity 
charges for showing his works the center and its director will be 
arraigned monday 
i wasnt starting out to make a statement that isnt the way 
i work mapplethorpe once said the statement grows out of what 
i do 
in his 197677 work bill mapplethorpe placed a mirror 
between two panels of a man masturbating the idea is to have the 
viewer see him or herself flanked by two erect penises 
he used the same technique in 1979s easter lilies with 
mirror here four panels form a cross around a center mirror 
the lilies are shown in dramatic shadows a dusting of light 
illuminating their inner and almost religious beauty 
it is a way of engaging the viewer beyond mere voyeurism the 
viewer becomes a part of the work 
in the triptych brice marden 1976 mapplethorpe shows the 
artist fullfigure sitting with his own work in the background a 
closeup in the center panel and the last panel blank it is a 
wonderful study in depth perception 
but the intense shadow composition of another triptych jim 
and tom sausalito 197778 is obliterated by the action in the 
picture in which one man urinates on another around the same 
time mapplethorpe did a selfportrait posed partly naked in 
leather with the handle of a bullwhip in his rectum 
they are among his most disturbing photographs part of a period 
in which he unraveled a violent homosexual mystique for an 
unsuspecting audience they are terrifying sadomasochistic 
tableaux chained men leatherbound men men prepared for pain in 
an aristocratic setting 
but despite the frightening roughness of these sexual and 
psychological images mapplethorpe succeeded in crafting a rich 
tonal range 
he was involved in an incredibly wide variety of life the 
other side of which is death said the artist lowell nesbitt who 
first met and befriended mapplethorpe in 197172 
its very clear that much of his photographs were mirrors of 
his personal life i think that mapplethorpe really wanted to be 
censored he was pushing for it he was pushing the artistic 
barriers the way many artists have in the past to see how far he 
could push before he could met a boundary 
back in the early 70s a time of rainbow drugs and easy sex of 
troubled politics and an unpopular war mapplethorpe was into 
jewelry 
he was an artist but he wasnt exactly painting said 
nesbitt he would refashion jewelry by adding materials to 
customize a piece for the owner 
mapplethorpe was one of six children born to joan and harry 
mapplethorpe he fled his catholic childhood in floral park 
queens for the bohemian earthiness of brooklyn in the 1960s 
there he received his art education at pratt institute 
it also was there that he encountered and forged a lasting 
friendship with radical poet and musician patti smith together 
they shared in each others work and supported each others dreams 
they were avantgarde hippies while others were still beatniks 
punk before the first british rude boy spat out the word outlaws 
while others were simply radical 
he spent his artistic lifetime photographing smith her 
portraits range from early polaroids to the portrait he used on her 
1988 lp dream of life 
the 1978 triptych patti smith still moving shows smith in 
muted tones intertwined with a flimsy curtain her clothes falling 
away her features slightly blurred a portrait in 1976 shows a 
vulnerable naked smith curled up on her haunches clinging to 
pipes in a barren studio 
mapplethorpe said there was little difference in photographing 
men or women its like sculpture finally working with a 
threedimensional form most of the people i photograph are not 
trained models or actors but they all have strong personalities 
he did portraits of actor richard gere artists louise nevelson 
and alice neel lawyer roy cohn body builder lisa lyon and 
transvestite candy darling and they were as varied as his 
classically poetic studies of flowers fruit and vegetables 
his great mentor was sam wagstaff the museum curator 
nesbitt said he introduced mapplethorpe to what were the most 
advanced forms of art going on in the united states at that time 
he probably helped develop mapplethorpes very personal eye and 
incredible ability to use light which was somewhat prophetic 
a lot of photographers are equally capable technically but it 
takes an artistphotographer to distinguish himself and what does 
this is a very personal eye 
mapplethorpes eye consumed more than merely the flat surface of 
a photo he infused light and shadow certainly but he also 
applied textures and tones using fabric and paint such as platinum 
on linen or mesh wire overlays his early work utilized collage for 
drama and movement 
photographs became not an end in themselves but the raw 
material for a works foundation in 1971 he painted over a 
yellowed torn childhood photo of artist andy warhol leaving one 
smiling eye his mouth and shoulder untouched 
in his last years his work was austere beauty was found in 
simplicity a 1988 picture titled nipple could be a parched 
desert the moons surface or a dried river bed but it is a 
closeup of the human form 
calla lily 1988 is a stark portrait of the sculpted 
flower and his study of a man named thomas in 1986 showed 
mapplethorpe in classic form a naked man strains against a circle 
a geometric work reminiscent of leonardo da vinci 
im sure he felt he had made an amazing achievement 
artistically nesbitt said he had the selfsatisfaction of 
considering himself a major influence 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
dolores barclay has been the ap arts and 
entertainment editor for 10 years 
</TEXT>
