<TEXT>
the rise of cattle futures prices to 
record levels this week hasnt brought euphoria to the industry 
where memories are vivid of the beefmarket crash that followed the 
previous highs a decade ago 
everyone is running scared right now and its the best 
thing said leon miller president of eagle passbased alta verde 
industries one of the nations top 20 cattle producers 
everyone remembers what happened when prices shot up last 
time if producers just keep selling especially with the prices 
up the market will continue to stabilize miller said 
live cattle futures reached a record price for the second 
consecutive day thursday on the chicago mercantile exchange with 
the april contract finishing at 8042 per hundredweight up from 
wednesdays 8040 
the previous high before this week 8025 per hundred pounds 
of beef in 1979 lasted only briefly before prices plummeted about 
25 percent 
although producers are mindful of that crash they say the 
market now isnt as vulnerable to a similar turnaround 
todays record prices reflect a seasonal peak in demand for beef 
and supply tightness stemming from delayed cattle marketings 
because of dry pastures in the southern plains last fall and winter 
we have a completely different situation said tommy beall 
director of research for cattlefax a denverbased market analysis 
company for the cattle 
the economics are different the prices we have seen recently 
accurately reflect the state of the industry the prices in 1979 
did not he said 
beall said liquidation by producers leaving the industry over 
the past decade has tightened the cattle supply and forced prices 
up 
the supply situation was much different in 1979 when inflated 
prices and overpopulated feed yards gave producers a false sense of 
security 
producers took females out of the slaughter and placed them in 
the breeding herds to multiply and cash in on the high prices back 
then miller said 
suddenly we had too many head of cattle and the bottom fell 
out miller said 
the 1979 crash caused prices to plummet from 80 per 
hundredweight to the 60 range in a matter of weeks 
that drop combined with rising production and grain costs and 
dry conditions have reduced the number of cattle head by 16 
million since the mid1980s beall said 
the industry is still recovering from the price drop said 
jim gill a market analyst for the texas cattle feeders 
association in amarillo the tight supply of cattle right now 
reflects the changes in the industry since the sharp drop in 
prices 
feeders and analysts agree that a new selling philosophy of 
expect less for cattle tomorrow than what you can get today 
has helped insure the market against another breakoff miller said 
industry officials said todays record futures prices would not 
affect retail beef costs because futures prices had been around the 
80 mark for two months 
the retail price increase has already been passed on to the 
consumer miller said when futures prices jumped from about 
74 to where they are now in february there was an increase in a 
few cents per cut 
most industry officials expect prices will ease in the next two 
months when grazing conditions are expected to improve and cattle 
can be beefed up more quickly but declines should be moderate 
they say 
i would expect the price to land at about 75 or 76 by june 
said milton rudder vice president of aztx cattle co based in 
hereford the number of cattle ready to be sold will increase 
significantly 
</TEXT>
