a specialist firm on the new york stock exchange 
was fined 480350 for securities fraud by a judge who said he 
imposed the sentence as a deterrent 
the trading while in possession of confidential material is a 
crime us district judge charles haight said thursday at the 
sentencing of marcus schloss amp co it constitutes an affront to 
the fair operation of the marketplace 
prosecutors said marcus schloss was the first nyse firm to be 
convicted of felony charges related to insider trading 
the company was convicted last july of conspiracy to trade on 
inside information and of securities fraud in connection with its 
march 1986 purchase of stock in american brands inc it was 
acquitted of securities fraud charges for stock trades involving 
three other companies 
marcus schloss could have been fined a maximum of 1 million 
500000 for each of two counts 
haight however said he only considered a fine of 500000 
because both charges stemmed from the american brands deal 
from that amount the judge said he subtracted 19650 which the 
company previously paid the securities and exchange commission to 
settle civil charges stemming from the american brands trade 
the sec settlement reached in february 1988 involved other 
trades and required marcus schloss to pay a total of 410000 
the firms lawyer marvin schwartz said the sec settlement was 
the companys plain acknowledgement of wrongdoing he told the 
judge that any additional fine would be in the nature of a double 
hit 
marcus schloss former head of arbitrage d ronald yagoda was 
tried with the firm but was acquitted of all charges including 
perjury and obstruction of justice in connection with an sec 
inquiry 
