<TEXT>
a 48 million federal lawsuit against 
honeywell inc and unisys corp alleges that a sperry aerospace 
operation honeywell bought from unisys in 1986 has been defrauding 
the navy for the past 11 years 
the business which honeywell resold in 1988 repeatedly 
inflated its estimated cost for flight simulators used to train 
pilots of f18 and t45 jets according to a lawsuit filed thursday 
by the us attorney in brooklyn ny 
the suit seeks 48 million in claims on government contracts 
which is triple the governments alleged loss of 16 million it 
also seeks 5000 to 10000 for each allegedly false claim for 
payment that was submitted to the government 
tim morin a honeywell spokesman said the firm had not seen a 
copy of the suit and declined to comment 
the simulator suit involves a business unit that 
minneapolisbased honeywell owned from 1986 to 1988 although the 
alleged fraud occurred over a period extending back to the late 
1970s during that time the business unit was owned first by 
sperry based in new york and later by detroitbased unisys which 
was formed when sperry was acquired by burroughs corp in 1986 
the governments suit claims that in 1979 sperry deliberately 
underestimated the cost of an initial project for the f18 
simulator hoping to obtain the contract for it and later projects 
it succeeded in winning those contracts but then concealed its true 
estimates of what the later projects cost the suit says 
instead the suit says executives padded the cost estimate by 
as much as 30 percent presenting the higher numbers to the navy 
and concealing the added amounts in labor charges 
the suit says documents showing the added dollars were 
distributed to a committee of company executives then collected 
after each committee meeting 
the result was inflated contract prices awarded by the 
government the lawsuit alleges 
the suit alleges the flight simulator project for the t45 was 
similarly inflated 
officials at the us attorneys office said the suit was filed 
in brooklyn federal court because the alleged fraudulent activities 
occurred in corporate offices in the new york area 
the suit is the third legal obstacle honeywell has encountered 
as a result of acquiring the sperry aerospace operations 
the first episode involved hidden contract costaccounting 
problems in the albuquerque nm military aerospace operations 
those problems were mainly responsible for honeywells record loss 
of 435 million in 1988 as a result of those problems honeywell 
in 1988 sued unisys for more than 350 million mostly over alleged 
misstatements about the financial condition of the sperry aerospace 
operations 
the second episode arose last year when the government sued 
honeywell and unisys for about 48 million over alleged contract 
violations at operations in albuquerque 
honeywell has said a significant part of that suit involves 
alleged incidents that occurred before it bought the operations 
from unisys damages for the period before honeywells ownership 
would be covered by a contract clause under which unisys would bear 
the costs for its period of ownership morin said 
</TEXT>
