<TEXT>
its been more than six months since ralph 
ingersoll ii and his st louis sun swaggered into this midwestern 
city armed with catchy slogans and ideas about the newspaper 
business 
ingersoll chairman and chief executive officer of ingersoll 
publications co named himself editorinchief and promised that 
the new tabloid would be the first profitable startup of a daily 
metropolitan newspaper in 40 years 
today the colorful newspapers future seems anything but clear 
the sun is struggling to overcome higherthanexpected costs 
revolvingdoor circulation limited advertising and a murky image 
that has turned critics into fans and fans into critics from day to 
day 
it seems as if things are not sailing along as smoothly as mr 
ingersoll had planned said charles klotzer editor and publisher 
of the st louis journalism review 
ingersoll says rumors of the newspapers imminent demise are 
greatly exaggerated 
on april 1 the newspaper had circulation of 109000 its 
highest yet and up from a low of 80000 during the winter thanks 
to the start of a new bingo promotion ingersoll said 
ingersoll has guaranteed advertisers circulation of 105000 for the 
first six months of 1990 
and the paper had 181 pages of advertising in the first week of 
april the suns best week since it began sept 25 
we have plenty of good news but we also have some problems 
and we need to make some changes ingersoll said in a telephone 
interview thursday the changes are all evolutionary not 
revolutionary 
ingersoll said that debt problems facing ingersoll publications 
had cast a shadow over the sun although they had no impact on the 
newspapers success or failure because they involved a separate 
company owned ingersoll 
last month ingersoll announced a plan to buy back some of 
community newspapers incs highinterest junk bonds at cutrate 
prices to appease some of his bondholders who were worried about 
the companys fiscal health 
we felt we might have a good business opportunity so we made 
the offer ingersoll said the reaction has been what you would 
expect the bondholders who bought the bonds at a low price are 
enthusiastic the bond holders who bought them at a higher price 
are less enthusiastic and thats where we are 
but although the two dont have a direct connection the 
publicity the bonds generated has spilled into the sun and its 
newsroom 
richard stevens the suns metro editor said editors are 
working hard to make sure the newsroom focused on business rather 
than rumors and gossip 
any time that we spend dealing with this kind of stuff is a 
negative but as far as it wasting a lot of our time its not a 
factor said stevens 
its unclear what the general reaction has been in st louis to 
the new newspaper 
although the sun has not weighted its local coverage toward 
sensational or titillating tabloidtype topics it still has gotten 
complaints from some readers that it sensationalized certain 
stories drawing criticism for example were its coverage of a 
politician involved in a sexual assault and of the fiveyear 
anniversary of an accident in which a man nearly was sawed in two 
the newspaper also has been chided for running photos of new 
womens swimsuits and lingerie 
but the sun also has been praised for its coverage of the effort 
to build a new domed stadium downtown and for its attention to the 
troubles facing st louis major air carrier trans world airlines 
some critics look down their noses at the suns flood of 
promotions fluorescent green billboards and many contests but sun 
executives defend the practice as the best way to attract new 
readers 
the papers marketing and editorial aspects are the least of 
ingersolls troubles 
the sun is losing more money than it expected according to 
ingersoll mainly because of higherthanexpected circulation costs 
and a whopping turnover rate among home subscribers 
ingersoll said the company has been forced to spend 5 million 
more than planned to distribute the sun because twice as many 
readers as expected wanted their papers delivered 
advertisers consider that to be very good but its much more 
expensive than we planned for ingersoll said 
home subscribers also have been canceling their subscriptions at 
a high rate which has left the newspaper with a 300 percent 
churn rate the churn rate is the rate at which a newspaper 
must sign up new subscribers to keep circulation at existing levels 
for example if a newspaper has 50000 home subscribers and it 
has to sign up 25000 new subscribers each year to keep its 
homedelivery base at 50000 the newspaper would have a churn rate 
of 50 percent 
ingersoll said the paper was researching the cause of its 
extremely high churn rate 
