market where meat packers reportedly paid 81 cents to 82 cents a 
pound for topquality cattle in recent days 
on the retail level a weekly price survey of 15 cuts of beef in 
nine us cities by the knightridder financial news service found 
an average price of 241 per pound thursday compared with 239 a 
week earlier and 229 a year ago 
analysts said the main reason for the rising prices is tight 
supplies of marketready cattle the situation reflects a decline 
in feedlot placements last year after cattle prices fell during the 
summer to less than 70 cents a pound said thomas morgan president 
of sterling research corp in arlington heights ill 
he said cattle typically are marketed within five months of 
being placed on feedlots to be fattened 
morgan said feedlot placements picked up again last fall and 
winter after dry weather caused poor grazing conditions in the 
southern plains 
the winter wheat wasnt growing enough to pasture so they 
pulled cattle off the pastures and sold them to feedlots in october 
through january he said 
